    icon: "💾",
    content: `**1. Dynamic Memory Allocation:**
- Memory is allocated for objects during the program's runtime (at execution time)
- Done in heap memory using the "new" keyword
- The heap allows for flexible memory allocation with varying sizes
- Memory remains available until the object is no longer referenced
- JVM performs garbage collection to reclaim unused memory

\`\`\`java
String dynamicString = new String("Dynamic memory");
int[] dynamicArray = new int[10];
\`\`\`

**2. Static Memory Allocation:**
- Memory is allocated for variables at compile time, before execution
- Used for variables declared with the "static" keyword
- Allocated in the "Method Area"
- Memory remains available throughout the program's execution
- Not automatically reclaimed during execution

\`\`\`java
public class Example {
    static int staticVariable = 42;
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] staticArray = new int[5];
    }
}
\`\`\`

**Summary:** Dynamic allocation uses "new" keyword at runtime in heap memory. Static allocation happens at compile time for fixed-size variables.`,
