    icon: "📖",
    content: `**1. Array:** Fixed-size data structure storing elements of the same type in contiguous memory. Accessed via index (0 to length-1).

**2. ArrayList:** Dynamic, resizable implementation of the List interface. Auto-resizes when elements are added/removed.

**3. 2D Array:** Array of arrays representing a matrix/table. Accessed using two indices (row, column).

**4. String:** Built-in class for a sequence of characters. Strings are immutable — values cannot be changed after creation.

**5. StringBuilder:** Mutable class for efficient string manipulation. Supports append, insert, and delete operations.

**6. Recursion:** A technique where a method calls itself. Has a base case (stops recursion) and recursive calls.

**7. Stack:** LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) data structure. Add/remove from one end (the top).

**8. Queue:** FIFO (First-In-First-Out) data structure. Add at rear (enqueue), remove from front (dequeue).

**9. Linked List:** Nodes containing a value and reference to the next node. Allows dynamic insertion/deletion.

**10. Binary Tree:** Hierarchical structure where each node has at most two children (left, right).

**11. BST:** Binary tree where left child < node < right child. Enables efficient searching and sorting.

**12. Generic Tree:** Each node can have arbitrary number of children.

**13. HashMap:** Hash table storing key-value pairs for efficient retrieval.

**14. Heap:** Tree-based structure satisfying the heap property (min-heap or max-heap).`,
